<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The plaintiff has delivered three improper affidavits from his counsel's law partner (Mr. Peter Tuovi) that are almost entirely on &ldquo;information and belief&rdquo; from his counsel (Mr. Bryan McPhadden). These affidavits ought to be struck for non-compliance with the established rules for solicitor's affidavits and, if they are not struck, Mr. McPhadden should be precluded from arguing the pending motions. That is the common law rule enforced by this Court, and it is among the <EM>Rules of Professional Conduct</EM>.</P>
<P>2. Lawyers cannot avoid this rule &ldquo;through the subterfuge of having someone else swear the affidavit based on information and belief&rdquo;,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Trempe v. Reybroek</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No. 369</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [Book of Authorities (&ldquo;BOA&rdquo;), Tab 12].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as Mr. McPhadden has attempted through Mr. Tuovi. It is well-established that lawyers who supply the evidence of the named affiant are also precluded from appearing as counsel. That is the case here, as each of the three affidavits state that, &ldquo;[e]xcept where otherwise specifically indicated below, I am advised of the following by Mr. McPhadden and verily believe same to be true.&rdquo; Mr. Tuovi then recounts contentious allegations, arguments, and opinions without ever specifically claiming to have personal knowledge of any claimed facts.</P>
<P>3. Solicitors' affidavits should be struck out: (1) where they assert contentious evidence; (2) where they contain speculation, argument, conclusions, and opinions; and (3) where they attempt to shield the true affiant from cross-examination. The impugned affidavits are replete with each of these substantive defects. Objections to specific paragraphs are outlined in charts below. But the defects are so many, and so intertwined, that the three affidavits should be struck in their entirety.</P>
<P>4. If the affidavits are not struck in their entirety, the specific paragraphs outlined below in the charts should be struck. Alternatively, if any paragraphs survive that are on information and belief from Mr. McPhadden, he should be precluded from appearing as counsel on the pending motions.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Context for this Motion to Strike Affidavits</TI>
<P>5. This motion to strike is brought by Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania and Watchtower Bible and Tract Society of New York, Inc. (&ldquo;U.S. Defendants&rdquo;) as a preliminary matter in advance of two motions returnable August 2, 2019 (the &ldquo;August Motions&rdquo;). The August Motions are: (1) the plaintiff's motion seeking to amend the statement of claim and add parties (the &ldquo;Plaintiff's Motion&rdquo;); and (2) the cross-motion of the U.S. Defendants for an Order setting aside service <EM>ex juris</EM> and declaring that the Court does not have jurisdiction to hear the action against them or the defendant that the Plaintiff's Motion seeks to add (the &ldquo;Jurisdiction Motion&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. The U.S. Defendant's Jurisdiction Motion is based on jurisdiction <EM>simpliciter</EM> and does not raise <EM>forum non conveniens</EM> as a ground to decline the exercise of jurisdiction. Accordingly, facts regarding the comparative convenience of for a are irrelevant (<EM>e.g.</EM>, the locations of witnesses or the comparative preferability of procedures). The only relevant facts are those that speak to whether there is a real and substantial connection between Ontario and either the U.S. Defendants or the proposed new U.S. defendant (Christian Congregation of Jehovah's Witnesses (&ldquo;CCJW&rdquo;)).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Shah v. LG Chem; Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 2628</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 10].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. At a case management conference on January 11, 2019, the plaintiff's counsel forecasted certain preliminary motions. The Court also scheduled the present motion to strike affidavits to be heard with the other preliminary issues.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Direction of The Honourable Justice Perell dated January 11, 2019: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 5, pp. 532-533.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. In view of their impropriety, counsel for the U.S. Defendants did not cross-examine Mr. Tuovi on his three affidavits, and instead wrote to counsel for the plaintiff to confirm that they would move to strike out the improper affidavits at the scheduled May 2 motion date.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>The Tuovi Affidavits Are the Evidence of Mr. McPhadden, Counsel on the August Motions</TI>
<P>9. The plaintiff has delivered three affidavits of Peter Tuovi, a partner in the law firm acting for the plaintiff in these proceedings.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Those affidavits are dated August 3, 2018 (the &ldquo;first Tuovi Affidavit&rdquo;), January 2, 2019 (the &ldquo;Second Tuovi Affidavit&rdquo;), and April 2, 2019 (the &ldquo;Third Tuovi Affidavit&rdquo;). Collectively, Mr. Tuovi's three affidavits are referred to as the &ldquo;Tuovi Affidavits.&rdquo;</P>
<P>10. The Third Tuovi Affidavit was delivered after plaintiff's counsel had already conducted its cross-examinations of the U.S. Defendants, and as such requires leave of this Court pursuant to Rule 39.02(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>. As set out below, leave should be refused because the Third Tuovi Affidavit is also inadmissible and improper.</P>
<P>11. The contents of the Tuovi Affidavits expressly constitute the evidence of Mr. Tuovi's law partner, Mr. Bryan McPhadden, who has carriage of this action on behalf of the plaintiff.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Each of the Touvi Affidavits states that &ldquo;[e]xcept where otherwise specifically indicated below, I am advised of the following by Mr. McPhadden and verily believe same to be true.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 7; Second Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 3, p. 148; Third Tuovi Affidavit, paras. 1, 3: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 4, pp. 450-451.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There are no paragraphs of the Tuovi Affidavits where Mr. Tuovi specifically claims to have personal knowledge of <BOLD><EM>any</EM></BOLD> facts. There are, however, a very small number of paragraphs where the source of Mr. Tuovi's information and belief is given as being the existing plaintiff in these proceedings, or as the proposed new plaintiffs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Second Tuovi Affidavit, paras. 7, 8, 10, and 15: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 3, pp. 150&ndash;152.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Jurisdiction and Test to Strike Out Affidavits</TI>
<P>12. This Court has the jurisdiction pursuant to Rules 4.06(2), 25.11, and 39.01(4) to strike out the Tuovi Affidavits on the basis that they contain improper, inadmissible, and irrelevant evidence, and are thus abusive, frivolous, vexatious, and will necessarily delay the August Motions. Exercising this jurisdiction prevents prejudice to the adverse party and wasted effort and expense.</P>
<P>13. Rule 4.06(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> states that &ldquo;[a]n affidavit shall be confined to the statement of facts within the personal knowledge of the deponent or to other evidence that the deponent could give if testifying as a witness in court, except where these rules provide otherwise.&rdquo;</P>
<P>14. Rule 39.01(4) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provides an exception to Rule 4.06(2) for motions: &ldquo;An affidavit for use on a motion may contain statements of the deponent's information and belief, if the source of the information and the fact of the belief are specified in the affidavit&rdquo;.</P>
<P>15. A court may strike out all or part of a document such as an affidavit pursuant to Rule 25.11 if the document (or parts thereof): (a) may prejudice or delay a fair trial; (b) is scandalous, frivolous, or vexatious; or (c) is an abuse of the process of the court.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This Court recently articulated the principles governing the exercise of this power as applied to affidavit evidence filed on a motion:
<ITEM><P>&ldquo;Improper hearsay, argument and irrelevant information should not be contained in an affidavit. [... ] [L]egal argument belongs in a factum or brief, and not an affidavit. Legal submissions contained in an affidavit are also superfluous, and should be struck out.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>&ldquo;Subject to specific exceptions, [... ] opinion evidence generally is impermissible and excluded. Witnesses generally are to testify as to the facts which they perceived, not as to the inferences/opinions they drew from them. It is for the trier and not the witness to form opinions, and draw inferences and conclusions. [... ] [E]ven properly qualified experts are to provide only opinion evidence that is fair, objective and nonpartisan.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6], citing <EM>inter alia</EM>, <CASEREF><SOC>White Burgess Langille Inman v. Abbott and Haliburton Co.</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2 S.C.R. 182</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Tab 13].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>&ldquo;Violations of the rules of evidence relating to affidavits are not mere technicalities or irregularities that may be cured or waived. To the contrary, where it is clear in law that affidavit evidence is inadmissible, leaving it on the record is embarrassing and prejudicial to the fair hearing of a motion or application.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>&ldquo;Evidence tendered in violation of the rules of evidence and <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> therefore must be regarded as worthless, and should not be considered; e.g., by the court refusing to receive the affidavit, striking the relevant paragraphs from the offending affidavit, and/or by the court otherwise paying no regard to the evidence.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></ITEM></P>
<P>16. Courts have held that an affidavit should be excluded entirely if it is not possible to separate admissible from inadmissible portions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Sharma v. Canadian Pacific Railway</SOC><CITE>2016 FC 135</CITE><PARANUM>19, 23</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 11].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Striking out the entire affidavit is appropriate where, as here, the impugned affidavits are riddled with inadmissible, improper, irrelevant and prejudicial statements which, when taken as a whole, render the affidavit itself as an abuse of process.</P>
<P>17. This is an appropriate case to strike out the Tuovi Affidavits on a preliminary motion because they are &ldquo;clearly improper and it would inevitably give rise to extraordinary cost or difficulty for the other party.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Allianz Global v. Attorney General of Canada</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 29</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 1].;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The extraordinary cost arises because the outcome of this motion will impact the ability of Mr. McPhadden to appear as counsel. If the Court decides not to strike the Tuovi Affidavits, the result will be that Mr. McPhadden cannot appear as counsel on the August Motions because doing so would constitute appearing on his own evidence. If this arose only in August, the August Motions would need to be adjourned, causing significant thrown-away costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>Improper Evidence from Counsel on the Motion</TI>
<P>18. This Court has established rules for the proper use of lawyers' affidavits, and the Tuovi Affidavits ignore those rules and should be struck. In <CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> this Court found a lawyer's affidavit both inadmissible and inappropriate, based on the following principles:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;If it is necessary to rely on the information or belief of counsel with carriage of the file, it is preferable for counsel to swear the affidavit and have other counsel argue the motion. This approach will not be appropriate for highly contentious issues that may form part of the evidence at trial. If the evidence of counsel becomes necessary for trial on a contentious issue, it may be necessary for the client to retain another law firm.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>14(b)</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4]. See also <CASEREF><SOC>Pavao v. Ferreira</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 1573</CITE><PARANUM>39</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 8].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;Unless the evidence of a lawyer is being tendered as expert testimony on the motion, it is not appropriate for an affidavit to contain legal opinions or argument. Those should be reserved for the factum.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>14(c)</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>19. The Court noted that a lawyer who provides an affidavit on matters that are not purely formal or uncontroverted risks contravening Rule 5.2 of the <EM>Rules of Professional Conduct</EM> (dealing with the professional limits of lawyers also acting as witnesses).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4.].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Court also warned lawyers not to give evidence on the merits of a matter (as Mr. Tuovi has done here),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <EM>e.g.</EM>, Second Tuovi Affidavit, paras. 7, 10: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 3, pp. 150-151.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as this risks the lawyer putting his credibility on the line and &ldquo;threaten[s]&rdquo; the &ldquo;integrity of the judicial system&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 41].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. This is particularly problematic where the lawyer gives opinions regarding the appropriate outcome of the proceeding, as this is &ldquo;implicitly criticizing the court should it come to a different view.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Messrs. Tuovi and McPhadden do this, for example, where they opine that CCJW is a &ldquo;proper and necessary defendant to this proceeding&rdquo; and that certain new people are &ldquo;proper and necessary plaintiffs.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 41: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This sworn opinion undermines the role of this Court and their status of counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. Where these rules are not followed, the offending paragraphs of an affidavit may be struck if they amount to &ldquo;substantive defects&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;merely formal defects&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Zanewycz v. Manryk</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3528</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 14].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Zanewycz v. Manryk</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court applied these principles and struck parts of a party's affidavit that were on &ldquo;information and belief&rdquo; from the counsel who appeared on the motion, and which went &ldquo;beyond merely summarizing evidence that was otherwise admissible from other sources.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Zanewycz v. Manryk</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3528</CITE><PARANUM>2, 4</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 14].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. Unless the Tuovi Affidavits are struck, Mr. McPhadden is precluded from arguing or appearing as counsel at the August Motions. It is well-established in Ontario that counsel who swears an affidavit on a motion&mdash;<BOLD><EM>or who supplies facts to another to swear on information and belief</EM></BOLD>&mdash;is precluded from appearing as counsel on that motion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Trempe v. Reybroek</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No 369</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, paras. 36&ndash;38 [BOA, Tab 12]; <CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is enforced by the courts<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gelinas v. Ucar</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1151</CITE><PARANUM>11-12</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 5]; <CASEREF><SOC>Bilich v. Toronto Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 2024</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 2].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and is a professional obligation under Rule 5.2-1 of the <EM>Rules of Professional Conduct</EM> (unless doing so is permitted by law in a given tribunal, or the matter is &ldquo;purely formal or uncontroverted&rdquo;).</P>
<P>23. This Court has held that &ldquo;[a] solicitor cannot avoid the rule that she cannot be a witness and counsel before the court through the subterfuge of having someone else swear the affidavit based on information and belief from her.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Trempe v. Reybroek</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No 369</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, para. 38 [BOA, Tab 12].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Further, &ldquo;[t]he only prohibition against Appearing on the affidavit of a member of one's own law firm arises where the information and belief of the deposing lawyer is in reality that of the lawyer appearing to argue the motion.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gelinas v. Ucar</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1151</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 5].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> That is the case here, as each of the Tuovi Affidavits state as a prelude for the entirety of the &ldquo;evidence&rdquo; given in the affidavits, that, &ldquo;[e]xcept where otherwise specifically indicated below, I am advised of the following by Mr. McPhadden and verily believe same to be true&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 7; Second Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 3, p. 148; Third Tuovi Affidavit, paras. 1, 3: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 4, pp. 450-451.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. The Tuovi Affidavits are not &ldquo;purely formal or uncontroverted&rdquo;, as they are replete with speculation, argument, conclusions, and opinions (as set out further below), which are improper and highly contentious. The U.S. Defendants and CCJW have given evidence setting out the factual basis for challenging the assertions of Messrs. Tuovi and McPhadden. Should either counsel appear on the August Motions, they will be in the embarrassing position of defending their own sworn statements against the sworn statements of persons who have personal knowledge.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>Improper Speculation, Argument, Conclusions, and Opinions</TI>
<P>25. Affidavits filed on a motion must be limited to statements of fact that are either within the affiant's personal knowledge, or which are believed to be true by the affiant based on information provided by a third party.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Csak v. Mokos</SOC><CITE>[1995] O.J. No. 4027</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Ct. J. (Gen. Div.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, paras. 13-14, 26 [BOA, Tab 3].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is impermissible for the affiant to speculate about facts, advance legal arguments, or draw conclusions from facts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6]; <CASEREF><SOC>Csak v. Mokos</SOC><CITE>[1995] O.J. No. 4027</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Ct. J. (Gen. Div.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, para. 26 [BOA, Tab 3]; <CASEREF><SOC>Pavao v. Ferreira</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 1573</CITE><PARANUM>43</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 8].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Legal submissions must be reserved for the factum.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. Witnesses who are not tendered as experts (such as Mr. Tuovi) may only give opinion evidence in certain limited circumstances, such as where a witness had an opportunity for personal observation and is thus in a better position than the trier of fact to form the conclusion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Graat</SOC><CITE>[1982] 2 S.C.R. 819</CITE><PAGENUM>pp. 837-838</PAGENUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 9].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> But if the trier of fact is in as good a position to form the conclusion, the opinion is inadmissible. It is not for Mr. Tuovi to read documents and draw inferences from what he reads, at least not in his affidavit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <CASEREF><SOC>White Burgess Langille Inman v. Abbott and Haliburton Co.</SOC><CITE>[2015] 2 S.C.R. 182</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Witnesses are to testify as to the facts which they perceived, not as to the inferences&mdash;that is, the opinions&mdash;that they drew from them&rdquo;) [BOA, Tab 13], <CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
