<P>28. The paragraphs indicated above as containing improper speculation as to the facts are objectionable regardless of the source of the speculation. There are only three possible sources. First (as suggested by the affidavits), this speculation constitutes inferences based on documents found on the Internet and attached to the Tuovi Affidavits. Inferences ought to be struck because &ldquo;[i]t is for the trier and not the witness to [...] draw inferences.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ismail v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 6780</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 6].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Second (as these paragraphs do not specifically state any other source), this &ldquo;evidence&rdquo; must be that of Mr. McPhadden.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>First Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 2, p. 7; Second Tuovi Affidavit, para. 1: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 3, p. 148; Third Tuovi Affidavit, paras. 1, 3: <EM>Motion Record</EM>, Tab 4, pp. 450-451.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If Mr. McPhadden has obtained this information from others, these paragraphs must be struck because they are double-hearsay, and because the source of the information is not specified or otherwise clear from the affidavit (contrary to Rule 39.01(4)).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Pavao v. Ferreira</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 1573</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 8].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Third (as the final possibility), if Mr. McPhadden claims to have personal knowledge, then he has made himself a witness of highly contentious evidence for trial. In that case, the firm of McPhadden, Samac, Tuovi LLP should be disqualified.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>14(b)</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>Improper Shielding of Plaintiff and Proposed Plaintiffs' Evidence</TI>
<P>29. Providing evidence on information and belief is not permissible as a vehicle to shield the true affiant from cross-examination.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>20140 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Accordingly, it is unacceptable to tender evidence on contentious issues on information and belief through a lawyer.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ferreira v. Cardenas</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 7119</CITE><PARANUM>14, 22</PARANUM></CASEREF> [BOA. Tab 4].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Second Tuovi Affidavit ignores this where it asserts that individuals advised Mr. Tuovi of their assault allegations, and that he believed them (as set out in the chart below). In addition to being irrelevant (as they go to the merits and confuse jurisdiction <EM>simpliciter</EM> with <EM>forum non conveniens</EM>), these paragraphs should be struck as improper attempts to shield evidence through an affiant without personal knowledge:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Metzler Investment GMBH v. Gildan Activewear Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3394</CITE><PARANUM>40, 54-55</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [BOA, Tab 7].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
